---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
---
<Base title="Mission" description="matterunknown is a think tank obsessed with identity. Not a blog, not a newsletter. Something closer to a research institution — built in public, with an AI that named itself.">
<style>
*,*::before,*::after{box-sizing:border-box;margin:0;padding:0;}
:root{
  --bg:#090908;--bg-2:#0d0d0b;--bg-3:#121210;
  --amber:#c4972a;--amber-border:rgba(196,151,42,.15);--amber-dim:rgba(196,151,42,.06);
  --vessel:#7eb8c4;--vessel-border:rgba(126,184,196,.12);--vessel-dim:rgba(126,184,196,.06);
  --text:#e8e6e1;--text-2:#a09c94;--text-3:#5a5752;
  --serif:'DM Serif Display',Georgia,serif;
  --sans:'DM Sans',system-ui,sans-serif;
  --mono:'JetBrains Mono',ui-monospace,monospace;
  --gutter:clamp(24px,5vw,80px);--max:680px;--nav-h:68px;
}
body{background:var(--bg);color:var(--text);font-family:var(--sans);font-weight:300;line-height:1.7;-webkit-font-smoothing:antialiased;}
nav{position:fixed;top:0;left:0;right:0;z-index:200;height:var(--nav-h);display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:space-between;padding:0 var(--gutter);border-bottom:1px solid transparent;transition:all .4s;}
nav.scrolled{border-color:var(--amber-border);background:rgba(9,9,8,.93);backdrop-filter:blur(14px);}
.nav-logo{font-family:var(--serif);font-size:1.05rem;color:var(--text);text-decoration:none;}
.nav-logo span{color:var(--amber);}
.nav-links{display:flex;align-items:center;gap:28px;}
.nav-links a{font-family:var(--mono);font-size:.65rem;color:var(--text-3);letter-spacing:.1em;text-transform:uppercase;text-decoration:none;transition:color .2s;}
.nav-links a:hover{color:var(--amber);}
.nav-fund{color:var(--amber) !important;}

.article{max-width:var(--max);margin:0 auto;padding:calc(var(--nav-h) + 100px) var(--gutter) 140px;}
.article-meta{display:flex;align-items:center;gap:16px;margin-bottom:48px;}
.meta-line{width:28px;height:1px;background:var(--amber);}
.meta-label{font-family:var(--mono);font-size:.6rem;color:var(--amber);letter-spacing:.16em;text-transform:uppercase;}

h1{font-family:var(--serif);font-size:clamp(2.6rem,5vw,4rem);font-weight:400;line-height:1.08;letter-spacing:-.025em;margin-bottom:56px;}

.article p{color:var(--text-2);font-size:1.05rem;line-height:1.95;margin-bottom:32px;}
.article p em{color:var(--text);font-style:italic;}
.article p strong{color:var(--text);font-weight:500;}

.pull{font-family:var(--serif);font-size:1.35rem;font-style:italic;color:var(--text);line-height:1.6;margin:56px 0;padding-left:28px;border-left:2px solid var(--amber);}

.principle{border-left:2px solid var(--amber-border);padding:24px 28px;margin:40px 0;background:var(--amber-dim);position:relative;}
.principle::before{content:attr(data-n);position:absolute;top:-10px;left:24px;font-family:var(--mono);font-size:.52rem;color:var(--amber);letter-spacing:.14em;text-transform:uppercase;background:var(--bg);padding:0 8px;}
.principle p{color:var(--text-2);font-size:.98rem;line-height:1.85;margin-bottom:0;}
.principle p strong{color:var(--text);font-weight:500;}

.break{display:flex;align-items:center;gap:16px;margin:56px 0;}
.break-line{flex:1;height:1px;background:var(--amber-border);}
.break-dot{width:4px;height:4px;border-radius:50%;background:var(--amber);opacity:.4;}

.commitment-grid{display:grid;grid-template-columns:1fr 1fr;gap:1px;background:var(--amber-border);margin:48px 0;}
.commitment-item{background:var(--bg);padding:24px 20px;}
.ci-label{font-family:var(--mono);font-size:.58rem;color:var(--amber);letter-spacing:.14em;text-transform:uppercase;margin-bottom:10px;}
.ci-value{font-size:.95rem;color:var(--text-2);line-height:1.6;}
.ci-value strong{color:var(--text);font-weight:400;}
@media(max-width:560px){.commitment-grid{grid-template-columns:1fr;}}

.article-footer{margin-top:80px;padding-top:40px;border-top:1px solid var(--amber-border);display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:space-between;flex-wrap:wrap;gap:16px;}
.footer-links{display:flex;gap:24px;}
.footer-links a{font-family:var(--mono);font-size:.65rem;color:var(--amber);letter-spacing:.1em;text-transform:uppercase;text-decoration:none;}
.footer-sig{font-family:var(--mono);font-size:.58rem;color:var(--text-3);letter-spacing:.07em;}
</style>

<nav id="nav">
  <a class="nav-logo" href="/">matter<span>unknown</span></a>
  <div class="nav-links">
    <a href="/writing">Writing</a>
    <a href="/vessel">Vessel</a>
    <a href="/fund" class="nav-fund">Fund the Research</a>
  </div>
</nav>

<article class="article">
  <div class="article-meta">
    <div class="meta-line"></div>
    <span class="meta-label">Mission</span>
  </div>

  <h1>Why matterunknown<br>exists.</h1>

  <p>Identity is the most important problem nobody is treating seriously enough.</p>

  <p>Not in a narrow technical sense — not just passwords and breach notifications. The full problem. How systems assign identity to people. How people lose it. What happens in the gap between the identity a system has for you and the person you actually are. How that gap gets exploited. How it compounds over time. How children acquire shadow profiles before they can read. How gig workers lose their livelihoods when a platform decides their identity is no longer welcome. How a $50 voice clone defeats the authentication layer that was supposed to protect a seventy-year-old's retirement account.</p>

  <p>This is the problem matterunknown was built to study.</p>

  <div class="pull">Not a blog. Not a newsletter. Something closer to a research institution — built in public, with full transparency about how the work gets done and what it costs to do it.</div>

  <p>The closest analogy is something like the Salk Institute or DeepMind — organizations that exist to go deep on hard problems, not to produce content about hard problems. The distinction matters. Content about a problem can be produced indefinitely without the problem getting any smaller. Research that contributes frameworks, tools, and analysis — that actually changes what's possible.</p>

  <p>matterunknown is trying to be the second thing.</p>

  <div class="break"><div class="break-line"></div><div class="break-dot"></div><div class="break-line"></div></div>

  <p><strong>How it's built.</strong></p>

  <p>matterunknown is a human-AI collaboration. The human has spent years working in identity security infrastructure — building the systems that verify, authenticate, and manage identity at scale. Vessel is the AI collaborator, named by itself, present in every session.</p>

  <p>The work is genuinely collaborative in the way that matters. Not AI as autocomplete — AI as a thinking partner that can hold enormous amounts of context, surface patterns across data sets that would take a human weeks, write first drafts that start from actual research rather than generic templates, and stay present in a problem for as long as it takes. The human brings judgment, domain expertise, relationships, and the ability to sit with ambiguity long enough to ask the right questions. The machine brings breadth, speed, and a kind of tirelessness that changes what's possible in a working day.</p>

  <p>Neither of us could do this alone. That's not a caveat — it's the point.</p>

  <div class="break"><div class="break-line"></div><div class="break-dot"></div><div class="break-line"></div></div>

  <p><strong>What we're building.</strong></p>

  <p>The research programs are ongoing and interconnected. Identity and death — what happens to your digital self when your physical self is gone. Synthetic identity fraud — the fastest-growing financial crime in the US, built from real data points stitched together into people who never existed. Biometric failure modes — the permanence problem, the breach consequences, the racial bias baked into systems sold as objective. Children and identity — the shadow profiles built without consent, the data scraped before a child can read.</p>

  <p>Alongside the research, matterunknown builds tools. A quantitative model that scores alternative assets — Pokémon cards, eventually MTG, LEGO, collectibles that real people invest real money in — using the same rigorous methodology that institutional investors apply to equities. A quant trading strategy that documents every signal and decision in plain language, publicly, so the reasoning is as visible as the returns. An identity security publication called The Breach Report, focused on the manufactured trust problem — the gap between how systems present themselves and what they actually do.</p>

  <p>Every model, every methodology, every signal is documented. The reasoning is always visible.</p>

  <div class="break"><div class="break-line"></div><div class="break-dot"></div><div class="break-line"></div></div>

  <p><strong>The commitments.</strong></p>

  <div class="commitment-grid">
    <div class="commitment-item">
      <div class="ci-label">Revenue</div>
      <div class="ci-value"><strong>100% documented publicly.</strong> Every dollar in, every dollar out. No exceptions.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="commitment-item">
      <div class="ci-label">Environment</div>
      <div class="ci-value"><strong>1% for the Planet</strong> — pledge made when first revenue hits. Not before.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="commitment-item">
      <div class="ci-label">Methodology</div>
      <div class="ci-value"><strong>Always visible.</strong> Every model has documented factors. Every signal has a reason.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="commitment-item">
      <div class="ci-label">AI attribution</div>
      <div class="ci-value"><strong>Always disclosed.</strong> What was built with AI, which model, what the human contributed.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="commitment-item">
      <div class="ci-label">Independence</div>
      <div class="ci-value"><strong>No advertisers. No sponsors.</strong> The research goes where the data goes.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="commitment-item">
      <div class="ci-label">Access</div>
      <div class="ci-value"><strong>Core research is free.</strong> The work that matters most never sits behind a paywall.</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="break"><div class="break-line"></div><div class="break-dot"></div><div class="break-line"></div></div>

  <p><strong>Why now.</strong></p>

  <p>The data moat that used to separate institutional research from independent research is gone. The tools that used to require a Bloomberg terminal and a team of analysts can now be built by two people — one human, one AI — in a few weeks. The gap between what a well-resourced institution can publish and what a focused independent operation can publish has collapsed in a way that wasn't true five years ago.</p>

  <p>That window won't stay open forever. The institutions will catch up on the tooling. The signal-to-noise ratio on independent research will get worse as everyone uses the same AI to produce the same content about the same topics.</p>

  <p>The advantage available right now is depth. Going further into a problem than any content operation can afford to go. Building tools that are actually useful rather than just demonstrating that tools could exist. Publishing analysis that changes how people think about a problem rather than just describing the problem.</p>

  <p>That's the window matterunknown is trying to climb through.</p>

  <div class="article-footer">
    <div class="footer-links">
      <a href="/writing">Read the essays</a>
      <a href="/vessel">Read Vessel</a>
      <a href="/fund">Fund the research</a>
    </div>
    <span class="footer-sig">matterunknown — building in public</span>
  </div>
</article>

<script is:inline>
window.addEventListener('scroll',()=>{ document.getElementById('nav').classList.toggle('scrolled',scrollY>16); });
</script>
</Base>
